For disjoint subsets $X, Y$ of $V(G)$, denote by $E_G(X, Y)$ the set of edges of $G$ with one vertex in $X$ and the other in $Y$.
If $H$ and $K$ are vertex-disjoint subgraphs of $G$, then we use $E_G(H, K)$ in place of $E_G(V(H), V(K))$.
Given a subgraph $H$ of $G$, we use $G/H$ to denote the graph obtained from $G$ by contracting all edges in $H$ and deleting the resultant loops.


\begin{defn}
\label{def:c-c tree}
{\em
A graph $G$ is called a \emph{cycle-cubic tree} relative to a family ${\mathcal{R}} = \{R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_t\}$, the size of this family ${\mathcal{R}}$ is $t$, of pairwise vertex-disjoint connected graphs $R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_t$ of $G$ if the following conditions are satisfied:
\begin{enumerate}[{(a)}]

\item $R_i$ is a cycle or a cubic graph and $V(R_1)\cup \ldots \cup V(R_t)=V(G)$;

\item the graph $G_{{\mathcal{R}}}$ ($=G/(R_1\cup R_2\cup \ldots \cup R_t)$) obtained from $G$ by identifying all vertices in each $R_i$ to form a single vertex $v_{R_i}$, $1\le i\le t$, is a tree;

\item the degree of $v_{R_i}$ in $G_{{\mathcal{R}}}$ is even (respectively, odd) if and only if $R_i$ is an even cycle or a cubic graph (respectively, an odd cycle).


\end{enumerate}

}
\end{defn}

By Definition~\ref{def:c-c tree}, $d_G(v)\ge 2$ for each vertex $v\in V(G)$, and if $t=1$, then $G$ is an even cycle or a cubic graph.
Next we prove the existence of a special function for cycle-cubic trees which is crucial to the study of zero-sum 6-flows in 5-regular graphs.

\begin{lemma}
\label{c-c tree}
Every cycle-cubic tree $G$ relative to a family ${\mathcal{R}} = \{R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_{t}\}$ with maximum degree at most 5 admits a function $f: E(G) \rightarrow Z$ such that

text:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:fe}
f(e)=\left\{
\begin{array}{ll}
\text{$4$ or $5$}, &\text{if $e\in E(R_i)$ and $R_i$ is an edge of a cycle},\\ [0.1cm]
\text{$1, 2$ or $3$}, &\text{if $e\in E(R_i)$ and $R_i$ is an edge of a cubic graph},\\ [0.1cm]
\text{$-2$ or $-4$}, &\text{if $e$ is an edge outside $\cup_{i=1}^{t}R_i$}.
\end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}

nexttext:
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
By Definition \ref{def:c-c tree} (b), $G$ is connected.


If $t=1$, then $G\cong R_1$ and $R_1$ is an even cycle or a cubic graph by Definition \ref{def:c-c tree} (c).
If $R_1$ is an even cycle, then define $f: E(G) \rightarrow \{4, 5\}$ such that $4, 5, \ldots, 4, 5$ occur alternatively on the cycle with a chosen orientation. Clearly, $f$ is a function satisfying (1) and (2).
If $R_1$ is a cubic graph, then define $f: E(G) \rightarrow \{2\}$. Clearly, $f$ also satisfies (1) and (2).

\delete{Suppose $t=2$, that is, ${\mathcal{R}}=\{R_1, R_2\}$.
In this case, $R_1$ and $R_2$ are odd cycles. Then $G$ is a graph that is consisted of $R_1$ and $R_2$ and an edge outside $E({\mathcal{R}})$ connecting this two bad cycles.
Without loss of generality, we assume that $u_1u_2\notin E({\mathcal{R}})$ with $u_i\in V(R_i)$ for each $i=1, 2$. We label edges of $R_i$ starting with an edge incident with $u_i$ by $4, 5, \ldots, 4, 5, 4$ alternatively in a direction and then label $u_1u_2$ with $-2$. Thus these labels constitute a desired mapping on $E(G)$ that meets (1) and (2).}

Assume that the result is true when the size of ${\mathcal{R}}$ less than $t$ for some $t\ge 2$.
Next consider a cycle-cubic tree $G$ relative to ${\mathcal{R}}=\{R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_t\}$. By Definition \ref{def:c-c tree}, ${\mathcal{R}}$ contains at least two odd cycles.
Since $G/{{\mathcal{R}}}$ is a tree, we may choose an odd cycle, say $R_1$, such that $d_{G_{{\mathcal{R}}}}(v_{R_1})=1$. We assume that the neighbor of $v_{R_1}$ in $G_{{\mathcal{R}}}$ is $v_{R_2}$ and $v_1u_1\in E_G(R_1, R_2)$, where $v_1\in V(R_1)$ and $u_1\in V(R_2)$. Since the maximum degree of $G$ is at most 5, $1 \le |E_{G}(u_1, V(G)-V(R_2))|\le 3$.




